adientBrush.StartPoint%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A> are relative to the area being painted."},{"content":"The point (0,0) represents the upper-left corner of the area being painted, and (1,1) represents the lower-right corner of the area being painted.","pos":[11957,12103]},{"content":"The default <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A&gt;</ph> of a <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush&gt;</ph> is (0,0), and its default <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A&gt;</ph> is (1,1), which creates a diagonal gradient starting at the upper-left corner and extending to the lower-right corner of the area being painted.","pos":[12104,12461],"source":" The default <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A> of a <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush> is (0,0), and its default <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A> is (1,1), which creates a diagonal gradient starting at the upper-left corner and extending to the lower-right corner of the area being painted."},{"content":"The following illustration shows the gradient axis of a linear gradient brush with default <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[12462,12679],"source":" The following illustration shows the gradient axis of a linear gradient brush with default <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A>."},{"pos":[12686,12875],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">![</bpt>Gradient axis for a diagonal linear gradient<ept id=\"p1\">]</ept><bpt id=\"p2\">(../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-diagonalgradientaxis.png \"</bpt>wcpsdk_graphicsmm_diagonalgradientaxis<ept id=\"p2\">\")</ept>","source":"![Gradient axis for a diagonal linear gradient](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-diagonalgradientaxis.png \"wcpsdk_graphicsmm_diagonalgradientaxis\")"},{"content":"The following example shows how to create a horizontal gradient by specifying the brush's <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[12882,13098],"source":"The following example shows how to create a horizontal gradient by specifying the brush's <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A>."},{"content":"Notice that the gradient stops are the same as in the previous examples; by simply changing the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A&gt;</ph>, the gradient has been changed from diagonal to horizontal.","pos":[13099,13380],"source":" Notice that the gradient stops are the same as in the previous examples; by simply changing the <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.StartPoint%2A> and <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush.EndPoint%2A>, the gradient has been changed from diagonal to horizontal."},{"content":"The following illustration shows the gradient that is created.","pos":[13814,13876]},{"content":"The gradient axis is marked with a dashed line, and the gradient stops are marked with circles.","pos":[13877,13972]},{"pos":[13979,14166],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">![</bpt>Gradient axis for a horizontal linear gradient<ept id=\"p1\">]</ept><bpt id=\"p2\">(../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-horizontalgradient.jpg \"</bpt>wcpsdk_graphicsmm_horizontalgradient<ept id=\"p2\">\")</ept>","source":"![Gradient axis for a horizontal linear gradient](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-horizontalgradient.jpg \"wcpsdk_graphicsmm_horizontalgradient\")"},{"content":"The next example shows how to create a vertical gradient.","pos":[14173,14230]},{"content":"The following illustration shows the gradient that is created.","pos":[14656,14718]},{"content":"The gradient axis is marked with a dashed line, and the gradient stops are marked with circles.","pos":[14719,14814]},{"pos":[14821,14995],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">![</bpt>Gradient axis for a vertical gradient<ept id=\"p1\">]</ept><bpt id=\"p2\">(../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-verticalgradient.jpg \"</bpt>wcpsdk_graphicsmm_verticalgradient<ept id=\"p2\">\")</ept>","source":"![Gradient axis for a vertical gradient](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-verticalgradient.jpg \"wcpsdk_graphicsmm_verticalgradient\")"},{"pos":[15038,15054],"content":"Radial Gradients","linkify":"Radial Gradients","nodes":[{"content":"Radial Gradients","pos":[0,16]}]},{"content":"Like a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush&gt;</ph>, a <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush&gt;</ph> paints an area with colors that blend together along an axis.","pos":[15058,15225],"source":"Like a <xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush>, a <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush> paints an area with colors that blend together along an axis."},{"content":"The previous examples showed how a linear gradient brush's axis is a straight line.","pos":[15226,15309]},{"content":"A radial gradient brush's axis is defined by a circle; its colors \"radiate\" outward from its origin.","pos":[15310,15410]},{"content":"In the following example, a radial gradient brush is used to paint the interior of a rectangle.","pos":[15417,15512]},{"content":"The following illustration shows the gradient created in the previous example.","pos":[15930,16008]},{"content":"The brush's gradient stops have been highlighted.","pos":[16009,16058]},{"content":"Notice that, even though the results are different, the gradient stops in this example are identical to the gradient stops in the previous linear gradient brush examples.","pos":[16059,16229]},{"pos":[16236,16410],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">![</bpt>Gradient stops in a radial gradient<ept id=\"p1\">]</ept><bpt id=\"p2\">(../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-4gradientstops-rg.png \"</bpt>wcpsdk_graphicsmm_4gradientstops_rg<ept id=\"p2\">\")</ept>","source":"![Gradient stops in a radial gradient](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-4gradientstops-rg.png \"wcpsdk_graphicsmm_4gradientstops_rg\")"},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.GradientOrigin%2A&gt;</ph> specifies the start point of a radial gradient brush's gradient axis.","pos":[16417,16556],"source":"The <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.GradientOrigin%2A> specifies the start point of a radial gradient brush's gradient axis."},{"content":"The gradient axis radiates from the gradient origin to the gradient circle.","pos":[16557,16632]},{"content":"A brush's gradient circle is defined by its <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.Center%2A&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusX%2A&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusY%2A&gt;</ph> properties.","pos":[16633,16870],"source":" A brush's gradient circle is defined by its <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.Center%2A>, <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusX%2A>, and <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusY%2A> properties."},{"content":"The following illustration shows several radial gradients with different <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.GradientOrigin%2A&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.Center%2A&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusX%2A&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusY%2A&gt;</ph> settings.","pos":[16877,17208],"source":"The following illustration shows several radial gradients with different <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.GradientOrigin%2A>, <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.Center%2A>, <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusX%2A>, and <xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush.RadiusY%2A> settings."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">![</bpt>RadialGradientBrush settings<ept id=\"p1\">]</ept><bpt id=\"p2\">(../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-originscirclesandradii.gif \"</bpt>wcpsdk_graphicsmm_originscirclesandradii<ept id=\"p2\">\")</ept>","pos":[17215,17392],"source":"![RadialGradientBrush settings](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/graphics-multimedia/media/wcpsdk-graphicsmm-originscirclesandradii.gif \"wcpsdk_graphicsmm_originscirclesandradii\")"},{"content":"RadialGradientBrushes with different GradientOrigin, Center, RadiusX, and RadiusY settings.","pos":[17395,17486]},{"pos":[17538,17600],"content":"Specifying Transparent or Partially-Transparent Gradient Stops","linkify":"Specifying Transparent or Partially-Transparent Gradient Stops","nodes":[{"content":"Specifying Transparent or Partially-Transparent Gradient Stops","pos":[0,62]}]},{"content":"Because gradient stops do not provide an opacity property, you must specify the alpha channel of colors using  <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[TLA#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tlasharptla-argb-md.md)]</ph> hexadecimal notation in markup or use the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromScRgb%2A?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> method to create gradient stops that are transparent or partially transparent.","pos":[17604,17977],"source":"Because gradient stops do not provide an opacity property, you must specify the alpha channel of colors using  [!INCLUDE[TLA#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tlasharptla-argb-md.md)] hexadecimal notation in markup or use the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromScRgb%2A?displayProperty=fullName> method to create gradient stops that are transparent or partially transparent."},{"content":"The following sections explain how to create partially transparent gradient stops in <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_xaml](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-xaml-md.md)]</ph> and code.","pos":[17978,18144],"source":" The following sections explain how to create partially transparent gradient stops in [!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_xaml](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-xaml-md.md)] and code."},{"pos":[18183,18217],"content":"Specifying Color Opacity in \"XAML\"","linkify":"Specifying Color Opacity in \"XAML\"","nodes":[{"content":"Specifying Color Opacity in \"XAML\"","pos":[0,34]}]},{"content":"In <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_xaml](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-xaml-md.md)]</ph>, you use  <ph id=\"ph2\">[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-argb-md.md)]</ph> hexadecimal notation to specify the opacity of individual colors.","pos":[18221,18443],"source":"In [!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_xaml](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-xaml-md.md)], you use  [!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-argb-md.md)] hexadecimal notation to specify the opacity of individual colors."},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-argb-md.md)]</ph> hexadecimal notation uses the following syntax:","pos":[18444,18563],"source":"[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-argb-md.md)] hexadecimal notation uses the following syntax:"},{"pos":[18570,18589],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`#`</ph> <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>aa<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>rrggbb<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>","source":"`#` **aa** *rrggbb*"},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>aa<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> in the previous line represents a two-digit hexadecimal value used to specify the opacity of the color.","pos":[18596,18708],"source":"The *aa* in the previous line represents a two-digit hexadecimal value used to specify the opacity of the color."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>rr<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>gg<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>bb<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept> each represent a two digit hexadecimal value used to specify the amount of red, green, and blue in the color.","pos":[18709,18843],"source":" The *rr*, *gg*, and *bb* each represent a two digit hexadecimal value used to specify the amount of red, green, and blue in the color."},{"content":"Each hexadecimal digit may have a value from 0-9 or A-F.","pos":[18844,18900]},{"content":"0 is the smallest value, and F is the greatest.","pos":[18901,18948]},{"content":"An alpha value of 00 specifies a color that is completely transparent, while an alpha value of FF creates a color that is fully opaque.","pos":[18949,19084]},{"content":"In the following example, hexadecimal <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-argb-md.md)]</ph> notation is used to specify two colors.","pos":[19086,19235],"source":"  In the following example, hexadecimal [!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_argb](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-argb-md.md)] notation is used to specify two colors."},{"content":"The first is partially transparent (it has an alpha value of x20), while the second is completely opaque.","pos":[19236,19341]},{"pos":[19612,19644],"content":"Specifying Color Opacity in Code","linkify":"Specifying Color Opacity in Code","nodes":[{"content":"Specifying Color Opacity in Code","pos":[0,32]}]},{"content":"When using code, the static <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromArgb%2A&gt;</ph> method enables you to specify an alpha value when you create a color.","pos":[19648,19791],"source":"When using code, the static <xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromArgb%2A> method enables you to specify an alpha value when you create a color."},{"content":"The method takes four parameters of type <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Byte&gt;</ph>.","pos":[19792,19852],"source":" The method takes four parameters of type <xref:System.Byte>."},{"content":"The first parameter specifies the alpha channel of the color; the other three parameters specify the red, green, and blue values of the color.","pos":[19853,19995]},{"content":"Each value should be between 0 to 255, inclusive.","pos":[19996,20045]},{"content":"An alpha value of 0 specifies that the color is completely transparent, while an alpha value of 255 specifies that the color is completely opaque.","pos":[20046,20192]},{"content":"In the following example, the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromArgb%2A&gt;</ph> method is used to produce two colors.","pos":[20193,20306],"source":" In the following example, the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromArgb%2A> method is used to produce two colors."},{"content":"The first color is partially transparent (it has an alpha value of 32), while the second is fully opaque.","pos":[20307,20412]},{"content":"Alternatively, you may use the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromScRgb%2A&gt;</ph> method, which enables you to use ScRGB values to create a color.","pos":[20655,20797],"source":"Alternatively, you may use the <xref:System.Windows.Media.Color.FromScRgb%2A> method, which enables you to use ScRGB values to create a color."},{"pos":[20837,20890],"content":"Painting with Images, Drawings, Visuals, and Patterns","linkify":"Painting with Images, Drawings, Visuals, and Patterns","nodes":[{"content":"Painting with Images, Drawings, Visuals, and Patterns","pos":[0,53]}]},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.ImageBrush&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.DrawingBrush&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows